1. JavaScript String primitives and core methods
- Strings exist as primitive values and as String objects. Prefer primitives; String constructor with new returns an object (type 'object').
- Common properties and methods (signatures and returns):
  - length: number property representing UTF-16 code units count.
  - String(x): function that coerces x to a string; handles Symbols by returning "Symbol(description)" when called as function (does not throw).
  - String.prototype.charAt(index): returns a string containing the UTF-16 code unit at index; index is a 0-based integer; returns empty string for out-of-range indices.
  - String.prototype.charCodeAt(index): returns numeric UTF-16 code unit value at index; NaN if index out of range.
  - String.prototype.codePointAt(pos): returns the Unicode code point value (handles surrogate pairs) at code unit index pos; returns undefined outside range.
  - String.prototype.substring(start, end): returns substring by UTF-16 code unit indices; end is optional.
  - String.prototype.slice(start, end): similar to substring but supports negative indices relative to end.
  - String.prototype.split(separator, limit): splits by separator; when separator is empty string, splits into UTF-16 code units (not grapheme clusters).
  - String.prototype.concat(...strings): returns concatenated string.
  - String.prototype.replace(searchValue, replaceValue): returns new string with replacements; accepts regex or string searchValue.
  - String.prototype.toUpperCase(), toLowerCase(): return new strings; behavior can be language-sensitive; use locale-specific methods when needed.
  - String.prototype.toLocaleLowerCase(locale), toLocaleUpperCase(locale): locale-aware case mapping.
  - String.prototype.valueOf(): returns primitive string value of String object.
  - String.prototype.localeCompare(compareString, locales?, options?): returns negative/0/positive number indicating lexicographic order under given locale and options. Options include sensitivity (base, accent, case, variant), usage, ignorePunctuation.
- Coercion rules: undefined -> "undefined", null -> "null", booleans -> "true"/"false", numbers -> numeric string, BigInt -> numeric string, Symbols when passed to String() -> "Symbol(desc)", objects -> toPrimitive then string.


2. Character access, indexing, and iteration levels
- Two access methods: charAt(index) and bracket notation str[index]. Bracket access is read-only. Both operate on UTF-16 code units, i.e., indices refer to 16-bit code units not full Unicode graphemes.
- Iteration via the string iterator (for...of or spread) iterates Unicode code points, not UTF-16 code units, so it yields full code points for surrogate pairs.
- Splitting with split("") yields array of UTF-16 code units and will split surrogate pairs. To iterate grapheme clusters (user-perceived characters) requires grapheme cluster segmentation logic (not provided by built-ins).


3. Case handling, locale-aware comparison, and coercion caveats
- toUpperCase/toLowerCase perform simple Unicode case mappings which are sometimes language-specific and may not be fully reversible (examples: German ß, Turkish dotted/dotless i). Use toLocaleLowerCase/toLocaleUpperCase or Intl.Collator/localeCompare for locale-sensitive equality and sorting.
- Recommended pattern for robust case-insensitive comparison: use Intl.Collator or String.prototype.localeCompare with options: sensitivity set to "accent" or "base" to ignore case/diacritics as required.
- When performing case-insensitive matching in RegExp with Unicode properties, be aware of differences between 'u' and 'v' mode with respect to how complement classes are case-folded (see Unicode property escapes section).


4. UTF-16, surrogate pairs, code points, grapheme clusters, well-formed strings
- JavaScript strings are sequences of UTF-16 code units. Characters outside the BMP are encoded as surrogate pairs (two 16-bit code units: high-surrogate 0xD800–0xDBFF followed by low-surrogate 0xDC00–0xDFFF).
- Lone surrogates are code units in the surrogate ranges that do not form a valid pair. They are invalid for some operations (e.g., encodeURI throws URIError for lone surrogates). Use String.prototype.isWellFormed() to check and String.prototype.toWellFormed() to produce a well-formed string.
- Code point escapes: \u{hex} notation (1–6 hex digits) represent Unicode code points; in source code, use when supported by parser.
- Grapheme clusters: multiple code points may form one user-perceived character (common for emoji sequences joined by ZWJ U+200D, or base + combining marks). Built-ins operate at code unit or code point level; grapheme segmentation requires external logic/libraries (Intl.Segmenter or third-party libraries) when available.


5. RegExp Unicode property escapes (syntax, flags, behavior)
- Syntax forms:
  - \p{LoneProperty}
  - \P{LoneProperty}
  - \p{Property=Value}
  - \P{Property=Value}
- LoneProperty: when used without explicit property= syntax, it applies to General_Category values or binary Unicode properties.
- Property names: ASCII letters and underscores only; values: ASCII letters, underscores, digits; both must match the Unicode Property Value Aliases defined by Unicode.
- Required flags: Unicode property escapes are meaningful only in Unicode-aware mode. Use the 'u' or 'v' regexp flags. Without the Unicode-aware flags, \p and \P are identity escapes for the letters p/P.
- Behavior differences between u and v modes:
  - In 'u' mode, \p{property} matches single code points and does not match property-of-strings sequences (like some emoji sequences).
  - In 'v' mode, \p{property} may match sequences (properties of strings) such as emoji sequences; intersection and set operators of the v-flag character class syntax enable composing multiple properties.
  - Case-folding with complement classes differs: in 'u' mode, case-folding happens after subtraction; in 'v' mode, case-folding happens before subtraction; this affects constructs like /\P{Lowercase_Letter}/i with u/v flags.
- Common property usages:
  - \p{L} or \p{Letter} matches Unicode letters across scripts.
  - \p{N} or \p{Number} matches Unicode numbers.
  - \p{Script=Latn} or \p{sc=Latn} matches Latin script characters; Script_Extensions can be used when characters belong to multiple scripts.
  - \p{Sc} matches currency symbols; combine with digits and punctuation to match prices.
- Flags and modifiers: append 'g' for global, 'u' for Unicode, 'v' for extended Unicode string properties (where supported), 'i' for case-insensitive; combining flags changes matching semantics as described above.


6. Lodash string transforms (camelCase, kebabCase) — transform rules and signatures
- _.camelCase(string) -> string
  - Normalization: splits input into words using separators (spaces, punctuation, underscores, hyphens, and case transitions), lowercases all words, capitalizes all words except the first, then concatenates without separators.
  - Removes non-alphanumeric characters by default; treats digits as part of words.
- _.kebabCase(string) -> string
  - Normalization: splits input into words similarly, lowercases all words, joins words using hyphen '-' as separator.
  - Result is suitable for URL slugs but not strictly identical to specialized slug libraries (which handle diacritics, locale mapping, non-Latin scripts, or removal rules).
- Signatures (canonical):
  - camelCase: function camelCase(input: string): string
  - kebabCase: function kebabCase(input: string): string


7. Levenshtein distance — definition, recursive formula, iterative DP algorithm, complexity
- Definition: Levenshtein distance lev(a,b) is the minimum number of single-character edits (insertions, deletions, substitutions) required to change string a into string b.
- Recursive formulation:
  - If |b| == 0 then lev(a,b) = |a|
  - If |a| == 0 then lev(a,b) = |b|
  - If head(a) == head(b) then lev(a,b) = lev(tail(a), tail(b))
  - Otherwise lev(a,b) = 1 + min( lev(tail(a), b), lev(a, tail(b)), lev(tail(a), tail(b)) )
- Iterative dynamic programming algorithm (matrix method):
  - Create matrix M of size (m+1) x (n+1) where m = length(a), n = length(b).
  - Initialize M[i][0] = i for i in 0..m, and M[0][j] = j for j in 0..n.
  - For i from 1..m, for j from 1..n:
    - cost = 0 if a[i-1] == b[j-1] else 1
    - M[i][j] = min( M[i-1][j] + 1,      // deletion
                     M[i][j-1] + 1,      // insertion
                     M[i-1][j-1] + cost) // substitution
  - Result is M[m][n].
- Complexity: time O(m * n), space O(m * n) for full matrix; can be reduced to O(min(m,n)) by keeping only two rows when only distance value is required.
- Use cases: fuzzy matching, spell checking, OCR correction, record linkage. Beware computational cost on long strings; typically applied to short tokens.


